Manifestations of CKD-MBD

CKD-mineral bone disease = hyperparathyroid bone disease = osteoporosis, osteomalacia, osteoscleroris, adynamic bone disease.
Basically, CKD patients have mixed bone disease.

Almost universal upon development of Stage III (i.e eGFR >= 30)

In addition to bone manifestations, ?metastatic calcification due to stimulation of endothelial cells to take own an osteoblast like phenotypes, so that they deposit calcified matrix.

  • Result is calcification of arteries -> hypertension and LVH
  • Calcification of heart valves

Pathogenesis of CKD-MBD

Phosphate excretion is handled by the kidney and resorption of filtered phosphate is a passive process, most occurring in the PCT.

  • Phosphate excretion falls, very early on in CKD.
  • To counteract this, osteocytes release FGF23 which promotes phosphaturia and reduces activation of vitamin D, thereby decreasing gut absorption of phosphate.

[!INFO] Elevated FGF23 levels are the strongest independent predictor of mortality in patients with CKD.

but as CKD progresses, this compensation is overcome.

[!INFO] Osteoporosis Vs. Osteomalacia

Osteomalacia Osteoporosis
Imparment of mineralization Mineral content is normal
matrix deposition in tact Total bone mass decreased

9: Lithium

Indications:
Lithium is used for prophylaxis of mania in bipolar patients. Not for acute treatment. For acute mania, antipsychotics and antiepileptics are equally effective.

Pharmacology

  • Very narrow therapeutic window. (therapeutic range is 0.5 to 1mmol/L and toxic effects start at 1.5 mmol/L)
  • It passes into cells via the sodium channels but is not pumped out via Na/K ATPase so accumulates within neurons.
  • Lithium preferentially affects organs with lots of sodium channels : I.e Brain and kidney and thyroid.
  • Exact mechanism of action is a mystery
  • Half of the oral dose is eliminated quickly by the kidneys. The rest is eliminated slowly over 2 weeks.
  • Therefore, it takes about 1 week for steady state concentrations. (Bennet and brown : 5 - 6 days, Rang and Dale : 1 - 2 weeks)
    • Lithium levels can be increased by hyponatremia because "the kidney treats lithium and sodium similarly and hyponatremia will cause increased lithium reabsorption" in the proximal tubule.
    • Diuretics acting distal to the PCT have a similar effect.
  • Toxicity:
    • Side effects occuring at therapeutic range: Fine tremor, polyuria, polydypsia, metallic taste, goiter, hypothyroidism,
    • Moderate toxicity : (plasma level > 1.5mmo/L) - GI: N/V/D and neuromuscular: Course tremor, weakness, ataxia, blurred vision
    • Severe toxicity: Medical emergency: hyperreflexia, hyperextension of limbs, convulsions, syncope and death.
    • Management of acute toxicity: improve renal elimination or dialysis (but dialysis only removes the plasma content. Cellular content is slow to shift to the plasma)
    • Drugs interfering with renal excretion of lithium: Thiazides > loop diuretics, ACEi, ARB, NSAIDS,
